In a meeting with Chancellor Brüning, Defense Minister Groener, General Schleicher, Finance Minister and Vice-Chancellor Hermann Dietrich, and our own Carl Severing, discussions focused on the upcoming presidential election and the organization of an effective propaganda campaign for Hindenburg. Severing outlined the threat that <span style="color: #7A3C00;">Nazism</span>—particularly the <span style="color: #7A3C00;">**SA**</span>—posed to state authority and emphasized the election's critical role in keeping the <span style="color: #7A3C00;">Nazis</span> in check.

All present agreed that a decisive victory for Hindenburg and a campaign free from violent disturbances would greatly accelerate Germany’s economic recovery and domestic political stabilization. Achieving this, however, would require the use of state funds. Dietrich himself passionately advocated for this, having secretly transferred 1.8 million marks to Severing and the Prussian government with the understanding that the funds would be distributed among various pro-Hindenburg organizations in the State of Prussia. This approach allowed Dietrich and the government to support pro-Hindenburg groups outside the right-wing United Hindenburg Committees.

